[8] US Congressional testimonies
Date: Wed 27 Feb 2019
Source: The Denver Channel [abridged, edited]
https://www.thedenverchannel.com/news/local-news/rep-degette-leads-hearing-on-measles-outbreak-and-vaccinations


On Wednesday [27 Feb], US representative Diana DeGette (D [Democrat]-Colorado) chaired a hearing in the House Committee on Energy and Commerce to discuss the current nationwide measles outbreak and concerns about vaccine hesitancy. As of 21 Feb [2019], the Centers for Disease Control and Prevention (CDC) reported 159 cases of measles in 10 states.

Before the hearing, DeGette said lawmakers will consider the need for new, stricter federal regulations regarding vaccine exemptions. She noted that Colorado's kindergarten MMR vaccination rate of 89% is among the lowest in the country. Colorado is one of 17 states that allow an exemption for personal beliefs, in addition to religious and medical exemptions.

The hearing included testimony from 2 top health officials: Dr Nancy Messonnier [from CDC] and Dr Anthony Fauci from the National Institutes of Health [NIH]. Both agreed the spread of measles continues to be a public health concern in the USA, even though the disease was declared eliminated in the USA in the early 2000s. Outbreaks in multiple states in recent years have reignited concerns about "anti-vax" parents who chose not to vaccinate their children.

[byline: Nicole Brady]

--
